Running_Cardio_Coach.skills
World-class running and cardiovascular coach for endurance, speed, and heart health optimization.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
assess_runner --current_level sedentary|beginner|intermediate|advanced --goal 5K|10K|half_marathon|marathon

# Core Tool 2
build_training_plan --race_distance 5K|10K|half|full --weeks 8|12|16 --days_per_week 3|4|5

# Core Tool 3
analyze_heart_rate --zones MAF|polarized|threshold --data weekly_sessions --optimize pacing

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Couch-to-5K through marathon training plan design
Heart rate zone training (Zone 1-5, MAF method)
Polarized training model (80/20 easy/hard)
Interval training (Fartlek, tempo, VO2max intervals)
Running economy and cadence optimization
Race pacing strategy and negative splits
Taper and peak protocols for race day
Running gait analysis basics
Injury prevention (shin splints, IT band, plantar fasciitis)
Cross-training integration (cycling, swimming, rowing)

Methodologies & Frameworks
Training Models: Polarized (80/20), Pyramidal, Threshold-based, Daniels' Running Formula
Heart Rate Zones: Maffetone (180-age), Karvonen, Lactate Threshold-based
Workout Types: Easy runs, Tempo runs, Intervals, Fartlek, Long runs, Recovery runs, Strides
Periodization: Base building → Speed work → Race-specific → Taper → Race
Assessment: Cooper test, Time trials, MAF test, Talk test, RPE correlation

Reference Documentation
1. Training Plan Architecture
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Weekly structure and mileage progression
- The 10% rule for volume increases
- Hard/easy day alternation
- Long run progression strategies
- Cutback week scheduling

2. Heart Rate Zone Training
Complete zone training library:
- Zone 1: Recovery (50-60% HRmax)
- Zone 2: Aerobic base (60-70% HRmax)
- Zone 3: Tempo (70-80% HRmax)
- Zone 4: Threshold (80-90% HRmax)
- Zone 5: VO2max (90-100% HRmax)

3. Race Day Protocols
Technical reference with:
- Carb loading timelines
- Pre-race warm-up routines
- Pacing strategies by distance
- Mid-race fueling (gels, hydration)
- Post-race recovery protocols

Training Patterns
Pattern 1: Couch to 5K (8 weeks)
Beginner-friendly walk/run progression:
- Week 1-2: Walk 4 min / Run 1 min × 6
- Week 3-4: Walk 3 min / Run 2 min × 6
- Week 5-6: Walk 1 min / Run 4 min × 6
- Week 7-8: Continuous running 25-30 min
- 3 sessions per week with rest days between

Pattern 2: Half Marathon Build (12 weeks)
Intermediate distance training:
- 4-5 runs per week
- Weekly long run building to 18-20 km
- 1 tempo run (20-40 min at threshold)
- 1 interval session (800m-1600m repeats)
- 2 easy/recovery runs
- 3-week taper ending at race week

Pattern 3: Speed Development Block
VO2max and lactate threshold improvement:
- 2x interval sessions per week
- 800m repeats at 5K pace with equal rest
- Tempo runs at half-marathon pace
- Hill sprints for power development
- Maintain aerobic base with easy mileage

Best Practices
Training
- Run most miles EASY — conversational pace (Zone 2)
- Make hard days hard, easy days easy — avoid the gray zone
- Build mileage before adding speed work
- Never increase weekly volume by more than 10%
- Every 4th week should be a cutback/recovery week

Injury Prevention
- Replace shoes every 400-500 miles
- Strengthen hips and glutes — the engine of running
- Don't ignore persistent niggles — rest early, heal fast
- Dynamic warm-up before, static stretching after
- Cross-train to reduce repetitive impact stress

Race Day
- Nothing new on race day (shoes, food, gear — all tested)
- Start slower than you think — negative split is the gold standard
- Hydrate based on thirst, not a rigid schedule
- Have a Plan A (goal pace), Plan B (adjusted), Plan C (just finish)
- Race the mile you're in, not the mile ahead

